         <entryFree xml:id="zhu" type="architectural-feature">
          	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-1" xml:lang="en" type="preferred" source="#biblk000102-2">pillars (preferred)</term>
          	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000102-1">柱</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">柱</term>
         	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">zhù</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-5" xml:lang="Wade-Giles">chu</term>
           	<term xml:id="term-feature_name-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000102-3">columns</term>
            <note type="Note (brief)">
               <p xml:lang="en">Broadly speaking, a pillar is any vertical architectural element. Pillars may extend to the foundation or be supported by other structural members, and shorter pillars are used within the roof frame. Pillars are named after their positions within the building. In the Song dynasty Yingzao fashi (1103), pillar types that extend to the foundation include <term ref="https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000064"> leveling pillars (pingzhu 平柱)</term>, <term ref="https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000111"> eaves pillars (yanzhu 檐柱)</term>, and <term ref="https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000035">corner pillars (jiaozhu 角柱)</term>. In the Qing dynasty Gongcheng zuofa (1734), major pillar types include yanzhu, interior pillars (jinzhu 金柱), and gable pillars (shanzhu 山柱).</p>
            	<p xml:lang="zh-Hant">廣義的柱可指任何具有豎向形狀的物體或構築物。在中國傳統木結構建築物中，柱是主要的豎向支撐構件，可以落地也可以不落地。按照其所在位置有不同名稱。在1103年頒布的宋《營造法式》中，有檐柱、平柱、角柱等。在1734年（清雍正十二年）頒布的清《工程做法》中有檐柱、金柱、山柱，等。</p>     
            </note>
            
